Path: godot/tutorials/vector_math.rst
Summary: Detecting if an object is facing another using vector math and dot product calculations

We can use this fact to detect whether an object is facing toward another object. In the diagram, the player P is trying to avoid zombies A and B. Assuming a zombie's field of view is 180°, can they see the player? The green arrows fA and fB are unit vectors representing the zombie's facing direction. The blue semicircle represents its field of view. For zombie A, we find the direction vector AP pointing to the player using P - A and normalize it. Godot has a helper method called direction_to() that performs this calculation. If the angle between this vector and the facing vector is less than 90°, then the zombie can see the player.

Note: The dot product between two vectors indicates the cosine of the angle between them. A positive result means the angle is acute (less than 90°).

GDScript:
var AP = A.direction_to(P)
if AP.dot(fA) > 0:
    print("A sees P!")

C#:
var AP = A.DirectionTo(P);
if (AP.Dot(fA) > 0)
{
    GD.Print("A sees P!");
}
---CHUNK---
